Semeion Handwritten Digit Data Set

1593 handwritten digits from around 80 persons were scanned, stretched in a rectangular box 16x16 in a gray scale of 256 values.

Source : https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Semeion+Handwritten+Digit

# First 256 elements of each row in the array represents the grayscale value of the 16x16 image of the numbers.
# The last 10 elements in each row of the array represents the actual number. 
# Only one of the 10 values will be 1 and the rest will be 0. 
# If the first of the 10 values is 1, then the number is 0. If the last of the 10 values is 1, then the number is 9.
# For our predictors we are interested in the image and not the actual number. 
# Hence we are excluding the last 10 values from each row for our 'X'
X = data[:,:-10]
print(X.shape)

Training network with 50 epochs¶

In [20]:
# Initiating the Neural Network model
model = Sequential()

# Add the first hidden layer which connects all the input layer nodes and a Bias Unit having value 1
model.add(Dense(100, activation='sigmoid', input_shape = (n_cols,), use_bias=True, bias_initializer='ones'))

# Output layer with a Bias Unit having value 1
model.add(Dense(n_categories, activation='sigmoid', use_bias=True, bias_initializer='ones'))
# https://towardsdatascience.com/activation-functions-neural-networks-1cbd9f8d91d6

# Create SGD optimizer with specified learning rate: my_optimizer
my_optimizer = SGD(lr=0.1)

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer=my_optimizer, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# For Stopping optimization when the validation loss hasn't improved for patience epochs. In this case 2 epochs
early_stopping_monitor = EarlyStopping(patience=2)

# Fit the model
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_split=0.3, epochs=50, verbose=2, callbacks=[early_stopping_monitor])
history

print('Train accuracy:',max(history.history['acc']))
print('Train loss:',min(history.history['loss']))

# https://www.quora.com/What-is-the-difference-between-keras-evaluate-and-keras-predict
# keras.evaluate() is for evaluating your trained model. Its output is accuracy or loss, not prediction to your input data.
score = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
print('Test accuracy:', score[1])
print('Test loss:', score[0])

# keras.predict() actually predicts, and its output is target value, predicted from your input data.
# Predicted values for each number and for each record
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Reference : https://nextjournal.com/gkoehler/digit-recognition-with-keras
# Plotting the accuracy : Epoch vs Accuracy
def plot_graph(history, n):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    plt.subplot(2,1,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['acc'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_acc'])
    plt.title('model accuracy when number of hidden layers =  '+str(n))
    plt.ylabel('accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['train'+str(n), 'validate'+str(n)], loc='lower right')
    fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=1)

    plt.subplot(2,1,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('model loss when number of hidden layers =  '+str(n))
    plt.ylabel('loss')
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['train'+str(n), 'validate'+str(n)], loc='upper right')
    plt.show()
    return plt.tight_layout()

plot_graph(history,50)

Function to develop Neural Network based on given configuration¶

In [34]:
def run_neural_network(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, hidden_layers_count, learning_rate, epoch_count):
    print('\nTesting model with number of hidden layers = ' + str(hidden_layers_count) + ', learning rate = ' + str(learning_rate) +   ', no. of epochs = ' + str(epoch_count) + '\n')
    
    # Initiating the Neural Network model
    model = Sequential()
    
    # Add the first hidden layer which connects all the input layer nodes and a Bias Unit having value 1
    model.add(Dense(hidden_layers_count, 
                    activation='sigmoid', 
                    input_shape = (n_cols,), 
                    use_bias=True, 
                    bias_initializer='ones'))
    
    # Output layer with a Bias Unit having value 1
    model.add(Dense(n_categories, 
                    activation='sigmoid', 
                    use_bias=True, 
                    bias_initializer='ones'))
    # https://towardsdatascience.com/activation-functions-neural-networks-1cbd9f8d91d6

    # Create SGD optimizer with specified learning rate: my_optimizer
    my_optimizer = SGD(lr=learning_rate)

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(optimizer=my_optimizer, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    # For Stopping optimization when the validation loss hasn't improved for patience epochs. In this case 2 epochs
    early_stopping_monitor = EarlyStopping(patience=2)
    
    # Fit the model
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_split=0.3, epochs=epoch_count, verbose=0, callbacks=[early_stopping_monitor])
    
    print('Train accuracy:',max(history.history['acc']))
    print('Train loss:',min(history.history['loss']))

    # keras.evaluate() is for evaluating your trained model. Its output is accuracy or loss, not prediction to your input data.
    score = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)
    print('Test accuracy:', score[1])
    print('Test loss:', score[0])
    
    # Plot the graph: Epochs vs Accuracy
    plot_graph(history, hidden_layers_count)
    
    # Predicted values for each number and for each record
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    #Getting the value of actual and predicted number for confusion matrix
    actual = np.argmax(y_test, axis = 1)  # Since each prediction is a one hot encoded array
    prediction = np.argmax(y_pred, axis = 1)  # Since each prediction is a one hot encoded array
    
    # Finding the Confusion Matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, prediction)

    # Visualizing Confusion Matrix
    plot_confusion_matrix(cm)
    
    # Print the Classification Report
    print('Classification Report: \n'+classification_report(actual, prediction))
    
    #Print Accuracy Score
    test_accuracy = accuracy_score(actual, prediction)
    print('Accuracy Score of the model: ' + str(test_accuracy))

Plot of both training and test accuracy as a function of epoch number:¶

Since the above graphs are of epoch accuracies of Train and Validation data, created a new function which prints the Epoch vs Accuracy graph for Train and Test data.

In [41]:
def epoch_vs_accuracy(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, hidden_layers_count, learning_rate, epoch_count):
    print('\nTesting model with number of hidden layers = ' + str(hidden_layers_count) + ', learning rate = ' + str(learning_rate) +   ', no. of epochs = ' + str(epoch_count) + '\n')
    
    # Initiating the Neural Network model
    model = Sequential()
    
    # Add the first hidden layer which connects all the input layer nodes and a Bias Unit having value 1
    model.add(Dense(hidden_layers_count, 
                    activation='sigmoid', 
                    input_shape = (n_cols,), 
                    use_bias=True, 
                    bias_initializer='ones'))
    
    # Output layer with a Bias Unit having value 1
    model.add(Dense(n_categories, 
                    activation='sigmoid', 
                    use_bias=True, 
                    bias_initializer='ones'))
    # https://towardsdatascience.com/activation-functions-neural-networks-1cbd9f8d91d6

    # Create SGD optimizer with specified learning rate: my_optimizer
    my_optimizer = SGD(lr=learning_rate)

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(optimizer=my_optimizer, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    # For Stopping optimization when the validation loss hasn't improved for patience epochs. In this case 2 epochs
    early_stopping_monitor = EarlyStopping(patience=2)
    
    # Fit the model
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), epochs=epoch_count, verbose=0, callbacks=[early_stopping_monitor])
    
    # Plot the graph: Epochs vs Accuracy
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    plt.subplot(2,1,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['acc'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_acc'])
    plt.title('model accuracy when number of hidden layers =  '+str(hidden_layers_count))
    plt.ylabel('accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['train'+str(hidden_layers_count), 'test'+str(hidden_layers_count)], loc='lower right')
    fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=1)

    plt.subplot(2,1,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('model loss when number of hidden layers =  '+str(hidden_layers_count))
    plt.ylabel('loss')
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['train'+str(hidden_layers_count), 'test'+str(hidden_layers_count)], loc='upper right')
    plt.show()
    return plt.tight_layout()

Effect of number of hidden units on the final accuracy on the test data:¶

As the number of units in the hidden layer increases, the Accuracy increases though not a significant amount. But it doesn't mean that increasing the number of units in the hidden layer will always increase the Accuracy. Just to prove that, I tried a large number of neurons in the hidden layer say 200 which reduces the accuracy. Increasing the number of units in the hidden layer increases the computational cost and may not be used when there is not considerable increase in the accuracy.

Finding the effect of number of hidden units on the number of epochs needed for training to converge:¶

def hidden_vs_epoch(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, hidden_layers_count, learning_rate, epoch_count):
    print('\nTesting model with number of hidden layers = ' + str(hidden_layers_count) +   ', no. of epochs = ' + str(epoch_count) + '\n')
    
    # Initiating the Neural Network model
    model = Sequential()
    
    # Add the first hidden layer which connects all the input layer nodes and a Bias Unit having value 1
    model.add(Dense(hidden_layers_count, 
                    activation='sigmoid', 
                    input_shape = (n_cols,), 
                    use_bias=True, 
                    bias_initializer='ones'))
    
    # Output layer with a Bias Unit having value 1
    model.add(Dense(n_categories, 
                    activation='sigmoid', 
                    use_bias=True, 
                    bias_initializer='ones'))
    # https://towardsdatascience.com/activation-functions-neural-networks-1cbd9f8d91d6

    # Create SGD optimizer with specified learning rate: my_optimizer
    my_optimizer = SGD(lr=learning_rate)

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(optimizer=my_optimizer, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    # For Stopping optimization when the validation loss hasn't improved for patience epochs. In this case 2 epochs
    early_stopping_monitor = EarlyStopping(patience=2)
    
    # Fit the model
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_split=0.3, epochs=epoch_count, verbose=0, callbacks=[early_stopping_monitor])
    
    #Finding the number of epochs
    n_epochs = len(history.history['loss'])
    print('Number of epochs:', n_epochs)

stored_values = {}
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/7719466/how-to-convert-a-string-to-a-function-in-python
dispatcher = {'SGD' : SGD, 'Adam' : Adam}

def best_neural_network(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, hidden_layers_count, hidden_activation, output_activation, optimizer, learning_rate, loss, epoch_count):  
    # Initiating the Neural Network model
    model = Sequential()
    
    # Add the first hidden layer which connects all the input layer nodes and a Bias Unit having value 1
    model.add(Dense(hidden_layers_count, 
                    activation=hidden_activation, 
                    input_shape = (n_cols,), 
                    use_bias=True, 
                    bias_initializer='ones'))
    
    # Output layer with a Bias Unit having value 1
    model.add(Dense(n_categories, 
                    activation=output_activation, 
                    use_bias=True, 
                    bias_initializer='ones'))
    # https://towardsdatascience.com/activation-functions-neural-networks-1cbd9f8d91d6

    # Create SGD optimizer with specified learning rate: my_optimizer
    my_optimizer = dispatcher[optimizer](lr=learning_rate)

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(optimizer=my_optimizer, loss=loss, metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    # For Stopping optimization when the validation loss hasn't improved for patience epochs. In this case 2 epochs
    early_stopping_monitor = EarlyStopping(patience=2)
    
    # Fit the model
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_split=0.3, epochs=epoch_count, verbose=0, callbacks=[early_stopping_monitor])
    
    # Evaluating the performance of the model in the test data
    score = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)

    #Storing the values
    if (len(stored_values))!=0: 
        i = (len(stored_values))/3 
    else: 
        i = 0
    stored_values['hidden_layers_count%d' % (i)] = hidden_layers_count
    stored_values['hidden_activation%d' % (i)] = hidden_activation
    stored_values['output_activation%d' % (i)] = output_activation
    stored_values['optimizer%d' % (i)] = optimizer
    stored_values['learning_rate%d' % (i)] = learning_rate
    stored_values['loss%d' % (i)] = loss
    stored_values['epoch_count%d' % (i)] = epoch_count
    stored_values['train_accuracy%d' % (i)] = max(history.history['acc'])
    stored_values['train_loss%d' % (i)] = min(history.history['loss'])
    stored_values['test_accuracy%d' % (i)] = score[1]
    stored_values['test_loss%d' % (i)] = score[0]

hidden_layers_counts = [20,50,100]
hidden_activations = [None, 'relu', 'tanh', 'sigmoid']
output_activations = ['softmax', 'sigmoid']
optimizers = ['SGD', 'Adam']
learning_rates = [0.01, 1, 10]
losses = ['binary_crossentropy', 'categorical_hinge', 'categorical_crossentropy']

# Varying the epochs isn't required since it will be automatically stopped by our EarlyStopping function with patience=2.
epoch_counts = [100]

i=0

    for hidden_activation in hidden_activations:
        for output_activation in output_activations:

hidden_layers_count = 100
hidden_activation = 'sigmoid'
output_activation = 'softmax'
optimizer = 'Adam'
dispatcher = {'Adam' : Adam}
learning_rate = 0.01
loss = 'binary_crossentropy'

# Initiating the Neural Network model
model = Sequential()

# Add the first hidden layer which connects all the input layer nodes
model.add(Dense(hidden_layers_count, 
                activation=hidden_activation, 
                input_shape = (n_cols,)))

# Add the second hidden layer which connects all the first hidden layer nodes
model.add(Dense(hidden_layers_count, 
                activation=hidden_activation))

# Output layer with a Bias Unit having value 1
model.add(Dense(n_categories, 
                activation=output_activation, 
                use_bias=True, 
                bias_initializer='ones'))

# Create SGD optimizer with specified learning rate: my_optimizer
my_optimizer = dispatcher[optimizer](lr=learning_rate)

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer=my_optimizer, loss=loss, metrics=['accuracy'])

# For Stopping optimization when the validation loss hasn't improved for patience epochs. In this case 2 epochs
early_stopping_monitor = EarlyStopping(patience=2)

# Fit the model
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_split=0.3, epochs=epoch_count, verbose=0, callbacks=[early_stopping_monitor])

# Evaluating the performance of the model in the test data
score = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)

print('train_accuracy',max(history.history['acc']))
print('train_loss',min(history.history['loss']))
print('test_accuracy',score[1])
print('test_loss',score[0])

In [38]:
def data():
    data = pd.read_csv("http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/semeion/semeion.data", 
                    delimiter = r"\s+",
                    header=None)
    data = np.asarray(data)
    data = data.astype(np.float)
    X = data[:,:-10]
    y = data[:,-10:]
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y,
                                                    stratify=y, 
                                                    test_size=0.3)
    return x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test

# Using different choices to try and find the best model
# hidden_layers_count = choice([20,50,100]
# hidden_activation = choice([None, 'elu', 'selu', 'relu', 'tanh', 'sigmoid']
# output_activation = choice(['softmax', 'sigmoid']
# optimizer = choice(['SGD', 'Adam', 'Adagrad', 'Adadelta', 'RMSprop']
# batch_size = choice([64, 128, 200]
# learning_rate = choice([0.01, 0.1, 1, 10]
# loss = choice(['categorical_hinge', 'categorical_crossentropy']

def create_model(x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test):
    dispatcher = {'SGD' : SGD, 'Adam' : Adam, 'Adagrad' : Adagrad, 'Adadelta' : Adadelta, 'RMSprop' : RMSprop}
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense({{choice([20,50,100])}}, 
                activation={{choice([None, 'elu', 'selu', 'relu', 'tanh', 'sigmoid'])}}, 
                input_shape = (256,), 
                use_bias=True, 
                bias_initializer='ones'))
    model.add(Dense(10, 
                activation={{choice(['softmax', 'sigmoid'])}}, 
                use_bias=True, 
                bias_initializer='ones'))
    my_optimizer = dispatcher[{{choice(['SGD', 'Adam', 'Adagrad', 'Adadelta', 'RMSprop'])}}](lr={{choice([0.01, 0.1, 1, 10])}})
    model.compile(optimizer=my_optimizer, loss={{choice(['categorical_hinge', 'categorical_crossentropy'])}}, metrics=['accuracy'])
    early_stopping_monitor = EarlyStopping(patience=2)
    history = model.fit(x_train, y_train, batch_size={{choice([64, 128, 200])}}, validation_data=(x_test, y_test), epochs=100, verbose=0, callbacks=[early_stopping_monitor])

    #get the highest validation accuracy of the training epochs
    validation_acc = np.amax(history.history['val_acc']) 
    print('Best validation acc of epoch:', validation_acc)
    return {'loss': -validation_acc, 'status': STATUS_OK, 'model': model}

# Testing the best parameters for checking the test data accuracy
hidden_layers_count = 100
hidden_activation = 'sigmoid'
output_activation = 'sigmoid'
optimizer = 'RMSprop'
dispatcher = {'RMSprop' : RMSprop}
batch_size = 128
learning_rate = 0.01
loss = 'categorical_hinge'

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y,
                                                    stratify=y, 
                                                    test_size=0.3)

# Initiating the Neural Network model
model = Sequential()

# Add the first hidden layer which connects all the input layer nodes
model.add(Dense(hidden_layers_count, 
                activation=hidden_activation, 
                input_shape = (n_cols,)))

# Add the second hidden layer which connects all the first hidden layer nodes
model.add(Dense(hidden_layers_count, 
                activation=hidden_activation))

# Output layer with a Bias Unit having value 1
model.add(Dense(n_categories, 
                activation=output_activation, 
                use_bias=True, 
                bias_initializer='ones'))

# Create SGD optimizer with specified learning rate: my_optimizer
my_optimizer = dispatcher[optimizer](lr=learning_rate)

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer=my_optimizer, loss=loss, metrics=['accuracy'])

# For Stopping optimization when the validation loss hasn't improved for patience epochs. In this case 2 epochs
early_stopping_monitor = EarlyStopping(patience=2)

# Fit the model
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, batch_size=batch_size, validation_split=0.3, epochs=100, verbose=0, callbacks=[early_stopping_monitor])

# Evaluating the performance of the model in the test data
score = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)

print('train_accuracy',max(history.history['acc']))
print('train_loss',min(history.history['loss']))
print('test_accuracy',score[1])
print('test_loss',score[0])
